    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Seems like the problem is even bigger:\n\n> 21:21 (+pchote) antares79: don't we cache TargetableUnit etc in a bunch of cases? \n> 21:21 (+pchote) that won't play nicely with turning them on/off \n> 21:22 (+antares79) pchote: with 'disable' I meant disabling using upgrades. that would be fine with caching, unless I'm terribly mistaken \n> 21:22 (+pchote) if you disable one without enabling another then you will have no targeting trait \n> 21:23 (+pchote) which means nothing can attack it \n> 21:23 (+antares79) hence the bug \n> 21:23 (+pchote) yup \n> 21:23 (+pchote) ...although, unless i'm missing something, I would call it intentional design \n> 21:23 (GraionDilach) ah yeah, multiple TargetableUnits still doesn't work lol \n> 21:23 (+antares79) yeah. it's just the wrong use case ;) \n> 21:24 (+pchote) what is that mission supposed to be doing? \n> 21:26 (+antares79) there are some infantry units of yours that are held captive by surrounding enemy units. those enemy units must be prevented from shooting at the captives somehow. previously, Cloak was used, since a few days ago it's TargetableUnit \n> 21:26 (+pchote) just make them not autotargetable \n> 21:26 (+pchote) via an upgrade \n> 21:27 (+antares79) yeah. or revert back to cloaking, that worked well. I don't know why it was changed. \n> 21:28 (+pchote) I think i remember seeing some comments about that being considered a hack \n> 21:55 (abcdefg30) anyway, i'm for support of multiple targetable unit traits \n> 21:55 (abcdefg30) we'll need that anyway for the targeting of airborne?\n"
